column7: s1: Honey never spoils. Archaeologists have found 3,000-year-old honey in Egyptian tombs that’s still edible.
column8: s2: Next Halloween costume idea: CEO and Head of HR.
column9: s3: A group of flamingos is called a “flamboyance.”
column11: s5: Well its settled then, it's not nearly as fun to hangout in a coffee shop as much as it is in a bar.
column12: s6: Went on a date to Wetherspoons. Either I’ve hit rock bottom… or I’ve peaked financially.
column13:
s7: Q: I'm two months pregnant now. When will my baby move?
A: With any luck, right after he finishes college.
column14: s8: In India, footpaths are for two things: walking and Salman Khan's driving practice.
column15: s9: Light travels faster than sound. That’s why some people appear bright until you hear them speak.
column16: s10: The inventor of the frisbee was turned into a frisbee. When he died, his ashes were molded into frisbees for his family and friends.
column17: s11: How do you know if a vampire is unwell? Because he'll be coffin.
column18: s12: There are more possible iterations of a game of chess than there are atoms in the observable universe.
column19: s13: I asked the barber for a ‘short back and sides’, he handed me a copy of The Sun and turned on Coronation Street.
column20: s14: Octopuses have three hearts: two pump blood to the gills, and one pumps it to the rest of the body.
column21: s15: I'm on a whiskey diet… I’ve lost three days already.
column22: s16: A statistical correlation without causation is simply a misleading relationship.
column23: s17: Two wrongs don’t make a right, take your parents as an example.
column24: s18: I took my 8-year-old to the office on Take Your Child to Work Day. As we were walking around, she starting crying & getting very cranky, so I asked her what was wrong. As my coworkers gathered round, she sobbed, 'Daddy, where are all the clowns that you said you worked with?'
column25: s19: Cleopatra lived closer to the invention of the iPhone than to the building of the Great Pyramid.
column26: s20: I asked the librarian if the library had books on paranoia. She whispered, “They’re right behind you.”
column27: s21: At Manchester airport and just seen a german woman smile to her pals, point out the window at a passing Jet2 plane and say in a strong german accent "nothing beats a Jet2 holiday".
column28: s22: [closes book, slowly removes glasses, and thoughtfully cleans them with a small cloth] I honestly don't think Waldo is in there
column29: s23: Bananas are berries, but strawberries aren’t. Botanically speaking, bananas qualify as berries, but strawberries do not.
column30: s24: The heart of a blue whale is so big that a human can swim through its arteries.
column31:
s25: BOSS: tell me about Susanne
ME: *takes a drag of cigarette* ah, the one that got away
BOSS: you're a zoo keeper none of them should get away.
column32: s26: After my youngest daughter fixed my computer, I overheard her talking with one of her friends saying it was just an "ID ten TerrorÂ”. They both starting laughing. Not wanting to appear dumb, I walked away and wrote down the code. ID10T. She was never my favorite kid anyway.
column33: s27: The fingerprints of a koala are so close to humans’ that they can taint crime scenes.
column34:
s28: Q: Should I have a baby after 35?
A: No, 35 children is enough.
column35: s29: A bolt of lightning contains enough energy to toast 100,000 slices of bread.
